<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1229,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,598,1229,1254]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Excavation locality and depository:</emphasis>
George Poinar, Jr. private collection (
<typeStatus box="[1073,1183,1229,1254]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Holotype</typeStatus>
: L-3-24)/ 
<collectingCountry name="Dominican Republic" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Dominican Republic</collectingCountry>
: Cordillera Septentrional between Santiago and 
<collectingRegion box="[792,931,1265,1290]" country="Dominican Republic" name="Puerto Plata" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Puerto Plata</collectingRegion>
, La Toca group of mines (Dominican Amber, La Toca Fm.)/Burdigalian, Early Miocene. The fossil was examined by JWB.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1229,2013]" box="[199,947,1337,1362]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,477,1337,1362]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Published illustrations:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W." box="[484,795,1337,1362]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="25 - 29" refId="ref13827" refString="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W. (1993) A new fossil tortricid (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) from Dominican amber. Entomologica Scandinavica, 23, 25 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631293 X 00028" type="journal article" year="1993">Poinar and Brown 1993: 26</bibRefCitation>
, 28, figs 1–3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1229,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1373,1398]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Condition:</emphasis>
The amber piece is roughly elliptical in shape (27 × 16 × 
<quantity box="[977,1047,1374,1398]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
). The fossil is an adult male with a forewing length of 
<quantity box="[369,459,1409,1434]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="5.8">5.8 mm</quantity>
. The specimen is entirely intact with most of the mouthparts and legs visible, and it is exceptional in that the wings are spread allowing the examination of the venation and showing a hint of raised scales. The elongate external portion of the valvae of the genitalia can also be observed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1229,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1517,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Comments:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W." box="[344,629,1517,1542]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="25 - 29" refId="ref13827" refString="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W. (1993) A new fossil tortricid (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) from Dominican amber. Entomologica Scandinavica, 23, 25 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631293 X 00028" type="journal article" year="1993">Poinar and Brown (1993)</bibRefCitation>
provide a detailed description and illustrations of the moth. The authors place the fossil with certainty in the extant subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[801,958,1553,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
based on the presence of the following characters: a generalized wing venation with hindwing veins M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[879,887,1604,1618]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">2</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[971,979,1604,1618]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">3</subScript>
widely distant, raised scale tufts on the forewing, and elongate valvae. Unfortunately, the most compelling morphological character that supports the monophyly of the subfamily is the presence of a deep longitudinal invagination on the male valva holding a hairpencil arising from the eighth abdominal segment (
<bibRefCitation author="Horak, M. &amp; Brown, R. L." box="[781,1038,1700,1725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="23 - 48" refId="ref12775" refString="Horak, M. &amp; Brown, R. L. (1991) 1.2 Taxonomy and phylogeny. In: van der Geest, L. P. S. &amp; Evenhuis, H. H. (Eds.), Tortricid pests, their biology, natural enemies and control. Elsevier Science Publishers B. V., Amsterdam, pp. 23 - 48." type="book chapter" year="1991">Horak &amp; Brown 1991</bibRefCitation>
), which is not visible on the fossil moth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1229,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
In the molecular phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[577,699,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Regier, J. C. &amp; Brown, J. W. &amp; Mitter, C. &amp; Baixeras, J. &amp; Cho, S. &amp; Cummings, M. P. &amp; Zwick, A." box="[754,995,1772,1797]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="35574" refId="ref14004" refString="Regier, J. C., Brown, J. W., Mitter, C., Baixeras, J., Cho, S., Cummings, M. P. &amp; Zwick, A. (2012) A molecular phylogeny for the leaf-roller moths (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) and its implications for classification and life history evolution. PLoS ONE, 7 (4), e 35574. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0035574" type="journal article" year="2012">
Regier 
<emphasis box="[841,904,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1012,1169,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
was not recovered as monophyletic, and a paraphyletic 
<taxonomicName box="[554,711,1808,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
was chosen as the working hypothesis. 
<bibRefCitation author="Regier, J. C. &amp; Brown, J. W. &amp; Mitter, C. &amp; Baixeras, J. &amp; Cho, S. &amp; Cummings, M. P. &amp; Zwick, A." box="[1200,1436,1808,1833]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="35574" refId="ref14004" refString="Regier, J. C., Brown, J. W., Mitter, C., Baixeras, J., Cho, S., Cummings, M. P. &amp; Zwick, A. (2012) A molecular phylogeny for the leaf-roller moths (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) and its implications for classification and life history evolution. PLoS ONE, 7 (4), e 35574. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0035574" type="journal article" year="2012">
Regier 
<emphasis box="[1287,1349,1808,1833]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
confirmed that 
<taxonomicName box="[322,479,1844,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
(as monophyletic or paraphyletic) are the most basal tortricid lineage and recognized the division of the subfamily into three tribes: 
<taxonomicName box="[671,797,1880,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
plus a monophyletic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Diakonoff" authorityYear="1977" box="[1038,1203,1880,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hilarographini">Hilarographini</taxonomicName>
+ Chlidanotini, with 
<taxonomicName box="[151,277,1916,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
as the first lineage to diverge. 
<bibRefCitation author="Fagua, G. &amp; Condamine, F. L. &amp; Horak, M. &amp; Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H." box="[635,853,1916,1941]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="449 - 466" refId="ref12375" refString="Fagua, G., Condamine, F. L., Horak, M., Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H. (2017) Diversification shifts in leafroller moths linked to continental colonization and the rise of angiosperms. Cladistics, 33 (5), 449 - 466. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / cla. 12185" type="journal article" year="2017">
Fagua 
<emphasis box="[712,770,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
also recovered a paraphyletic 
<taxonomicName box="[1204,1361,1916,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
as the basal-most lineages of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[408,534,1952,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1229,2013]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,647]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<bibRefCitation author="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W." box="[199,483,1988,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="25 - 29" refId="ref13827" refString="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W. (1993) A new fossil tortricid (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) from Dominican amber. Entomologica Scandinavica, 23, 25 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631293 X 00028" type="journal article" year="1993">Poinar and Brown (1993)</bibRefCitation>
exclude the moth from Chlidanotini and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Diakonoff" authorityYear="1977" box="[945,1110,1988,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hilarographini">Hilarographini</taxonomicName>
because of differences in the morphology diagnostic of these tribes (e.g., members of these tribes lack raised scales of the forewing and most have conspicuously thickened antennae). Characters indicating that the moth likely belongs to 
<taxonomicName box="[1220,1346,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
include the termination of vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[435,443,238,252]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">5</subScript>
before the apex of the wing found in many 
<taxonomicName box="[940,1070,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
; the presence of raised scales on the forewing, and the presence of elongate valvae in the male genitalia. However, the authors consider the assignment of the fossil specimen to this tribe tentative because the most convincing synapomorphies of the tribe are in the male genitalia, which are not visible in the fossil specimen. Nonetheless, we consider this specimen to be a member of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[299,425,370,395]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,647]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poinar &amp; Brown" authorityYear="1993" box="[199,391,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Polyvena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horatis">
<emphasis box="[199,391,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Polyvena horatis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was used by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fagua, G. &amp; Condamine, F. L. &amp; Horak, M. &amp; Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H." box="[552,772,406,432]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" pagination="449 - 466" refId="ref12375" refString="Fagua, G., Condamine, F. L., Horak, M., Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H. (2017) Diversification shifts in leafroller moths linked to continental colonization and the rise of angiosperms. Cladistics, 33 (5), 449 - 466. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / cla. 12185" type="journal article" year="2017">
Fagua 
<emphasis box="[630,689,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
to give a minimum age to 
<taxonomicName box="[1090,1251,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
. This use of the fossil is problematic because, as noted above, the subfamily is not monophyletic. 
<bibRefCitation author="Fagua, G. &amp; Condamine, F. L. &amp; Horak, M. &amp; Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H." box="[1060,1271,442,467]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" pagination="449 - 466" refId="ref12375" refString="Fagua, G., Condamine, F. L., Horak, M., Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H. (2017) Diversification shifts in leafroller moths linked to continental colonization and the rise of angiosperms. Cladistics, 33 (5), 449 - 466. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / cla. 12185" type="journal article" year="2017">
Fagua 
<emphasis box="[1135,1183,442,467]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">et al</emphasis>
. (2017)
</bibRefCitation>
chose to place the calibration point at the crown of 
<taxonomicName box="[580,706,478,503]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
following the suggestion by 
<bibRefCitation author="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W." box="[1046,1340,478,503]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" pagination="25 - 29" refId="ref13827" refString="Poinar, G. O. &amp; Brown, J. W. (1993) A new fossil tortricid (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) from Dominican amber. Entomologica Scandinavica, 23, 25 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631293 X 00028" type="journal article" year="1993">Poinar and Brown (1993)</bibRefCitation>
that the moth could belong in this tribe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,647]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
Currently, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poinar &amp; Brown" authorityYear="1993" box="[320,512,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Polyvena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horatis">
<emphasis box="[320,512,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Polyvena horatis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most thoroughly described fossil tortricids. Although the specimen does not display the full suite of characters characteristic of 
<taxonomicName box="[824,981,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chlidanotinae">Chlidanotinae</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[1018,1147,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Polyorthini">Polyorthini</taxonomicName>
, the visible characters are in favor of this placement.
</paragraph>
